To find the intersection points, we need to solve the equation $\sin x = 2\sin\left(3x - \frac{\pi}{6}\right)$.

Using the triple angle formula, we have 
$$\sin\left(3x - \frac{\pi}{6}\right) = \sin 3x \cos \frac{\pi}{6} - \cos 3x \sin \frac{\pi}{6} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\sin 3x - \frac{1}{2}\cos 3x.$$Substituting this into the original equation and simplifying, we get
$$\sin x = \sqrt{3}\sin 3x - \cos 3x.$$Using the sum-to-product formula, we can rewrite the right-hand side as
$$\sqrt{3}\sin 3x - \cos 3x = 2\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\sin 3x - \frac{1}{2}\cos 3x\right) = 2\sin\left(3x - \frac{\pi}{3}\right).$$Thus, we have 
$$\sin x = 2\sin\left(3x - \frac{\pi}{3}\right).$$Let $\theta = 3x - \frac{\pi}{3}$.  Then $x = \frac{\theta}{3} + \frac{\pi}{9}$, and our equation becomes
$$\sin \left( \frac{\theta}{3} + \frac{\pi}{9} \right) = 2 \sin \theta.$$We can graph $y = \sin \left( \frac{\theta}{3} + \frac{\pi}{9} \right)$ and $y = 2 \sin \theta$ on the interval $0 \le \theta \le 6 \pi$:

